Syntax highlighting for the D programming language is currently not functional. Looking at the static/feature/file-content/source-view/source-view.js file, support is there but it's set to use the .a file extension. It should be using .d and .di as the file extensions. Uploading a file with the .a extension is highlighted as D should be.

Very basic example file:

import std.stdio;

void main() {
	writeln("Test!");
}

For [delegated LDAP authentication|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/STASH/Configuring+delegated+LDAP+authentication] as well as for [LDAP integration with read/write access|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/STASH/Configuring+an+LDAP+directory], the messaging for "default group memberships" and "copy user on login" needs to be updated to also include the information that the user can also authenticate when using their Git pull/clone requests.
Currently the help text for this option seems to indicate that the only way for this property to take effect is when the user logs into the application via the UI. It should also include the user git pull/clone actions.
{quote}
Users are copied from your LDAP server into Stash when they authenticate. Copied users can subsequently be modified in Stash, but modifications will not be reflected on the LDAP server.
{quote}
{quote}
A comma-separated list of groups that users will be added to when they first log in. These groups will be created if they don't already exist.
{quote}

This is an issue identified by NCC Group during their recent review of the Stash application. Issue code in the report: STASH1-9.

Stash stored in clear-text the HipChat Hook plugin configuration settings. This included the configured HipChat API key.

It appears that the plugin service doesn't provide a means to store sensitive configuration settings securely. The data gathered from the user is submitted via a PUT request to the RepositoryHookResource class where it is transformed into an instance of a Settings object, a map-like container to store arbitrary configuration settings.

*Source code snippet*

plugins\rest\src\main\java\com\atlassian\stash\rest\repository

{quote}
\RepositoryHookResource.java#159
@PUT
@Path("{hookKey}/enabled")
public Response enableHook(
        @Context Repository repository,
        @PathParam("hookKey") String hookKey,
        @HeaderParam("Content-Length") @DefaultValue("0") int contentLength,
        @Context ContainerRequest request) {
    // This is a workaround for jersey not allowing optional request bodies
    //noinspection unchecked
    Map<String, Object> rawSettings = contentLength > 0 ?
            request.getEntity(Map.class) :
            null;

    RepositoryHook descriptor = rawSettings != null ?
            repositoryHookService.enable(repository, hookKey, createSettings(rawSettings)) :
            repositoryHookService.enable(repository, hookKey);

    return ResponseFactory
            .ok(TO_REST.apply(descriptor))
            .build();
}
{quote}

As discussed in issue STASH-2-5 (see previous report), it was possible to open the local Stash database and query it without supplying any credentials. Repository hook configuration settings were stored in the STA_REPO_SETTINGS table as shown below:
 
*Recommendation*

Protect the HipChat API token (and any other sensitive information) before storing it in the database. Consider using AES encryption with a per-installation key securely generated during the setup process.
Ideally a product-wide solution should be created to allow plugins to store sensitive information securely.

As an interim solution it may be possible to implement the encryption on the HipChatNotifyHook class directly by applying the encryption after the API token is validated but before the Settings are passed to the framework for storage:

plugins\rest\src\main\java\com\atlassian\stash\rest\repository\RepositoryHookResource.java	159
plugins\hipchat-integration\src\main\java\com\atlassian\stash\plugin\hooks\hipchat\HipChatNotifyHook.java	94

Creating based on customer's request:
{quote}
We only greenlight users into repositories if they're working on the project - otherwise, they should have no visibility to the repo. We achieve this by setting all projects to default to no access.

However, some folks will not follow directions and will change this setting when creating repositories. We would like to disable this setting so that it can never be set to anything other than No Access. Is this possible? As we occasionally give access to external clients, this is fairly critical to us to ensure that clients never have access to other clients' code.
{quote}

